---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "DevOps Toolkit: Docker, Git, Nginx & SSH Guide",
      "description": "A practical DevOps guide covering Docker, Git workflows, Nginx configuration, SSH key management, cron jobs, and server administration for developers.",
      "url": "https://siliconbased.dev/guide-devops-complete",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "SiliconBased"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between Docker and a VM?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Docker containers share the host operating system's kernel and isolate the application processes, making them lightweight and fast to start. Virtual Machines (VMs) include a full guest operating system on top of a hypervisor, making them heavier and slower but providing stronger isolation."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is a cron expression explained?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A cron expression consists of five fields representing Minute, Hour, Day of the month, Month, and Day of the week. For example, '0 0 * * *' means the task will run at midnight every day."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to set up SSH keys for server access?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "To set up SSH keys, use 'ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C \"your_email@example.com\"' to generate a key pair. Then, use 'ssh-copy-id user@server_ip' to copy your public key to the remote server's ~/.ssh/authorized_keys file, enabling passwordless authentication."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between git merge and git rebase?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Git merge creates a new commit that combines two branches, preserving the history of both. Git rebase moves the feature branch's commits to the tip of the target branch, creating a cleaner, linear history but rewriting the commit IDs."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why use Nginx as a reverse proxy?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Nginx as a reverse proxy sits in front of backend servers and forwards client requests to them. It helps with load balancing, SSL termination, caching, and serving static files efficiently, improving security and performance."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};

export const meta = {
  title: "DevOps Toolkit: Docker, Git, Nginx & SSH Guide",
  description: "A practical DevOps guide covering Docker, Git workflows, Nginx configuration, SSH key management, cron jobs, and server administration for developers.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="siliconbased"
  title="DevOps Toolkit: Docker, Git, Nginx & SSH Guide"
  description="A practical DevOps guide covering Docker, Git workflows, Nginx configuration, SSH key management, cron jobs, and server administration for developers."
  canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/guide-devops-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-5 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-6">DevOps Toolkit: Docker, Git, Nginx &amp; SSH Guide</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-12 text-lg leading-relaxed">
      Welcome to the comprehensive DevOps guide. Whether you're configuring a new server, containerizing your application, or setting up a deployment pipeline, mastering these core tools is essential for modern software development. Dive into our practical insights on Docker, Git, Nginx, SSH, Cron, and more.
    </p>

    <!-- Section 1: Docker Fundamentals -->
    <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">1. Docker Fundamentals</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Docker revolutionized how we package and deploy applications. Understanding containers is the first step to mastering modern DevOps. If you're new, check out our <a href="/guide-docker-basics" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Docker basics guide</a> or the comprehensive <a href="/guide-docker" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Docker tutorial</a>.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Containers vs VMs</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        While Virtual Machines (VMs) virtualize hardware to run an entire OS, Docker virtualizes the operating system. Containers share the host OS kernel, making them lightweight, fast to start, and less resource-intensive compared to VMs.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Dockerfile Essentials</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        A <code>Dockerfile</code> is a blueprint for building Docker images. It contains instructions like <code>FROM</code> (base image), <code>WORKDIR</code> (setting the directory), <code>COPY</code> (transferring files), and <code>CMD</code> (the default command to run).
      </p>
      <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-color)] mb-4 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] overflow-x-auto">
<pre><code>FROM node:18-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
COPY . .
CMD ["npm", "start"]</code></pre>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Docker Compose</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        When your application requires multiple services (e.g., a web app and a database), Docker Compose allows you to define and run multi-container Docker applications using a single <code>docker-compose.yml</code> file.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: Git Mastery -->
    <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">2. Git Mastery</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Version control is the backbone of collaboration. Mastering Git goes beyond basic commits. For a quick reference, keep our <a href="/git-cheat-sheet" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Git cheat sheet</a> handy, and learn more about <a href="/guide-git-commands" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">advanced Git commands</a>.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Branching Strategies</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Adopting a clear branching strategy (like GitFlow or GitHub Flow) ensures smooth collaboration. Typically, you have a <code>main</code> branch for production-ready code, a <code>develop</code> branch for integration, and feature branches for individual tasks.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Rebase vs Merge</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        When integrating changes from one branch into another, you have two main options:
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-2 ml-4">
          <li><strong>Merge:</strong> Combines branches by creating a new merge commit. It preserves the complete history and chronological order.</li>
          <li><strong>Rebase:</strong> Reapplies your commits on top of the target branch. It creates a linear, cleaner history but rewrites commit hashes.</li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Mastering .gitignore</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        The <code>.gitignore</code> file tells Git which files (like build artifacts, logs, or sensitive credentials) to ignore. If you need help generating one, try our <a href="/gitignore-generator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">.gitignore generator</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: Nginx Configuration -->
    <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">3. Nginx Configuration</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Nginx is a high-performance web server that excels as a reverse proxy, load balancer, and HTTP cache. To easily generate configuration files, check out our <a href="/nginx-config" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Nginx config tool</a>.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Reverse Proxy Setup</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        A reverse proxy receives client requests and routes them to backend servers (like a Node.js app running on port 3000). This setup abstracts the backend infrastructure and improves security.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">SSL Termination</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Handling SSL/TLS encryption at the Nginx level (SSL termination) offloads the cryptographic burden from your application servers and centralizes certificate management.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: SSH Keys & Server Access -->
    <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">4. SSH Keys &amp; Server Access</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Secure server access is non-negotiable. Password authentication should be disabled in favor of SSH keys. For a deeper dive, read our <a href="/guide-ssh-keys" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">guide on SSH keys</a>, and master command-line tools with our terminal guide.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Key Generation</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Modern systems prefer the <code>Ed25519</code> algorithm for generating SSH keys due to its security and performance.
      </p>
      <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-color)] mb-4 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--accent-color)] overflow-x-auto">
        ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">SSH Config File</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Manage multiple servers efficiently using the <code>~/.ssh/config</code> file. It allows you to define aliases, specify custom identity files, and set connection parameters automatically.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 5: Cron Jobs & Task Scheduling -->
    <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">5. Cron Jobs &amp; Task Scheduling</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Automating routine tasks like backups, log rotations, and data syncing is handled by the <code>cron</code> daemon on Unix-like systems.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Cron Expressions</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        A cron expression defines the schedule. It consists of five fields: minute, hour, day of month, month, and day of week. If you need help translating these, try our <a href="/cron-expression-generator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">cron expression generator</a>, explore our <a href="/crontab-guru" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">crontab guru alternative</a>, or use the basic <a href="/cron-generator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">cron generator</a>.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-color)] mb-4 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] overflow-x-auto">
        # Run a backup script every day at 2:30 AM
        30 2 * * * /path/to/backup.sh
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 6: .htaccess & Apache -->
    <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">6. .htaccess &amp; Apache</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        If you're using Apache instead of Nginx, directory-level configuration is managed via <code>.htaccess</code> files. They are vital for URL rewriting, redirects, and setting up security headers. Use our <a href="/htaccess-generator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">.htaccess generator</a> for common setups.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">Redirects and Rewrites</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Enforcing HTTPS or redirecting old URLs to new ones prevents broken links and preserves SEO rankings. The <code>mod_rewrite</code> module handles these efficiently.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 7: Deployment Pipeline -->
    <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">7. Deployment Pipeline</h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD) bridge the gap between development and operations by automating the build, testing, and deployment phases.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mt-6 mb-3">GitHub Actions and Automated Deploys</h3>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4">
        Tools like GitHub Actions allow you to define workflows via YAML files in your repository. You can configure pipelines to run tests on every pull request, build Docker images on merge, and deploy updates to your servers automatically via SSH.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 8: FAQ -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-6">8. Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">What is the difference between Docker and a VM?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Docker containers share the host operating system's kernel and isolate the application processes, making them lightweight and fast to start. Virtual Machines (VMs) include a full guest operating system on top of a hypervisor, making them heavier and slower but providing stronger isolation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How is a cron expression explained?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">A cron expression consists of five fields representing Minute, Hour, Day of the month, Month, and Day of the week. For example, <code>0 0 * * *</code> means the task will run at minute 0, hour 0 (midnight) every day.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How to set up SSH keys for server access?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Use <code>ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"</code> to generate a key pair. Then, use <code>ssh-copy-id user@server_ip</code> to securely append your public key to the remote server's <code>~/.ssh/authorized_keys</code> file, enabling passwordless login.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">What is the difference between git merge and git rebase?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><code>git merge</code> creates a new commit that combines two branches, preserving the exact history. <code>git rebase</code> moves your feature branch commits to the tip of the target branch, creating a clean linear history but rewriting the commit IDs.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Why use Nginx as a reverse proxy?</h3>
          <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Nginx acts as an intermediary, receiving external requests and forwarding them to backend servers. It provides benefits like load balancing, SSL termination, caching, and serving static files efficiently, ultimately improving both security and performance.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="related-tools" style="margin-top:3rem;padding-top:2rem;border-top:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.2rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">🔗 Related Tools</h2>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:1rem;">
      <a href="/guide-ssh-keys" style="display:block;background:rgba(255,255,255,0.03);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);border-radius:10px;padding:1.25rem;text-decoration:none;color:inherit;transition:border-color 0.2s,transform 0.2s;" onmouseover="this.style.borderColor='rgba(255,255,255,0.2)';this.style.transform='translateY(-2px)'" onmouseout="this.style.borderColor='rgba(255,255,255,0.08)';this.style.transform='none'">
        <strong style="font-size:0.95rem;">SSH Key Setup: Generate, Configure & Use SSH Keys</strong>
        <p style="opacity:0.6;font-size:0.83rem;margin:0.4rem 0 0;line-height:1.4;">Think your server is secure? 80% of developers mess up this one crucial step. Master SSH key generation and server setup...</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
